# Python Standards

## Principles

- DRY: extract repeated logic into shared modules
- KISS: prefer simple, readable code over clever abstractions
- YAGNI: don't build what isn't needed yet
- Fail fast: validate inputs early, raise meaningful exceptions
- Single responsibility: one function/module = one job

## Python Style

- Python 3.12+ — use modern syntax (type unions with `|`, `match` statements)
- Type hints on all function signatures and return types
- Use `ruff` for linting and formatting, `mypy` in strict mode
- Use `uv` as package manager
- Prefer `dataclasses` or Pydantic `BaseModel` for structured data
- No mutable default arguments

## Architecture (manu-eye)

Flat structure until complexity demands otherwise:

```
src/
  camera.py       # OpenCV capture loop
  decoder.py      # QR decode + dedup
  client.py       # HTTP client to manu-gen backend
  config.py       # env vars / settings
  main.py         # entry point
```

## Error Handling

- Define custom exception classes inheriting from a base `AppError`
- Never use bare `except:` — always catch specific exceptions
- Log errors with context using `structlog` or stdlib `logging`

## HTTP Client

- Use `httpx.Client` (sync) for outbound HTTP calls — the camera capture loop is blocking, so async adds complexity without benefit
- Reuse a single `httpx.Client` instance for connection pooling
- Consider `httpx.AsyncClient` only if the service moves to an async event loop

## Testing

- Use `pytest` for tests
- Name tests: `test_should_[behaviour]_when_[condition]`
- Arrange-Act-Assert structure
